Manually writing Swagger docs? üòì It's time to level up your workflow and let your code generate the docs for you ‚Äî automatically!

If you're using Spring Boot, the best way to do this is with:
Springdoc OpenAPI is a free, open-source integration that automatically generates Swagger UI and OpenAPI 3 documentation from your Spring Boot REST APIs. No manual effort required ‚Äî just annotate your controllers as usual!
pom.xml





<dependency>
  <groupId>org.springdoc</groupId>
  <artifactId>springdoc-openapi-ui</artifactId>
  <version>1.7.0</version> <!-- use latest -->
</dependency>

üì¶ Works with Maven ‚Äî use the corresponding dependency for Gradle if needed.
Once your app is running, open your browser and visit:
http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui/index.html

üéâ You'll see a full, interactive Swagger UI with all your API endpoints, parameters, responses, and models!
REST Controllers (@RestController)
Mappings like @GetMapping, @PostMapping, etc.
Bean validation annotations (@NotNull, @Size, etc.)
Spring Security annotations (with extra config)
Custom documentation with:


@Operation
@ApiResponse
@Parameter
For exporting your API or generating clients:
http://localhost:8080/v3/api-docs

Returns the OpenAPI 3 JSON spec!
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api")
public class UserController {

  @GetMapping("/users")
  public List<User> getAllUsers() {
    return userService.getAllUsers();
  }

  @PostMapping("/users")
  public User createUser(@RequestBody @Valid User user) {
    return userService.createUser(user);
  }
}

The above controller will automatically show in Swagger UI ‚Äî no extra setup needed!
Using Springdoc OpenAPI is a quick win for any Java microservice project. It ensures:
‚úÖ Always up-to-date documentation
ü§ù Easier collaboration with frontend/backend/devops
üöÄ Faster onboarding for new devs
üßπ Eliminates outdated manual Swagger files
